---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'CrossDrop Privacy – Your Files Never Touch Our Servers';
const description =
  'CrossDrop privacy policy: files transfer peer-to-peer with mandatory WebRTC encryption, no accounts, no contact access, no file storage, and no tracking of individual transfers.';
---

<Base {title} {description}>
  <article class="wrap article">
    <p class="eyebrow">Privacy</p>
    <h1>Privacy policy</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      CrossDrop is built so that there is almost nothing about you for us to
      know. This page explains the little that happens, in plain language.
    </p>

    <h2>Your files never touch our servers</h2>
    <p>
      Files transfer directly between your two devices over a peer-to-peer
      WebRTC connection. They are never uploaded to, stored on, or relayed
      through our infrastructure. We could not read your files even if we
      wanted to — they simply don't pass through us.
    </p>

    <h2>Everything is encrypted in transit</h2>
    <p>
      WebRTC connections are encrypted with DTLS as a mandatory part of the
      protocol. This is encryption by design, not an added feature that can
      be switched off.
    </p>

    <h2>What the pairing server sees</h2>
    <p>
      To connect two devices, each briefly talks to our signaling server to
      exchange connection details (session descriptions and network
      candidates). The server holds this in memory only for the seconds
      pairing takes, never writes it to disk, and discards the room as soon
      as the devices connect or either one leaves. It never sees file
      names, sizes, types, or contents.
    </p>

    <h2>No accounts, no contacts, no tracking</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No accounts or logins — we collect no names, emails, or phone numbers.</li>
      <li>No access to your contact list, and no discovery by phone number or Apple ID.</li>
      <li>No cookies beyond what's functionally necessary for a session.</li>
      <li>No analytics that fingerprint individual transfers or individual users.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Questions</h2>
    <p>
      If anything here is unclear, read the technical walkthrough on the
      <a href="/how-it-works">how it works</a> page — it describes exactly
      what moves where.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .article { max-width: 44rem; padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.5rem); }
  .lede { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .article h2 { margin-top: 2rem; }
</style>
